<body lang=EN-GB style='tab-interval:36.0pt'>

<div class=Section1>

<p class=MsoNormal>…Even after his musings upon Berant the Bard, which in
itself showed a great upsurge in consideration for others, Tagelied was not
fully reconciled to his task.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>He
managed to find Barbarians in Blackburrow who were preparing to leave for
Halas, and with their help he must have felt confident he could safely traverse
the treacherous passes.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>However, his
first contact with northern culture was not to be so uneventful...</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Master Lutestringer, 37<sup>th</sup> Circle, Historical
section, from his introduction to the compiled travels of Tagelied HalfElven. </p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><u><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>The Second Report.<o:p></o:p></span></u></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Your Graces,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-right:-2.55pt'>I beg leave to report that I
have arrived at Halas, crude capital of the Barbarians, and have made contact
with our representative here, Marton Stringsinger.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>He has assured me that this message will be dispatched to you as
quickly as may be arranged.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Much has
happened since my last missive.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-right:-2.55pt'><span style='mso-tab-count:
1'>                </span>After three days in Blackburrow, with backpacks
becoming heavy and food running low, the good Berant and his colleagues were
eager to return to Qeynos.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I wished
nothing more than to come with them, but loyal to my vows I was bound for
Halas.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Berant said he knew a way
whereby this could be achieved.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>The
overground areas of Blackburrow are places where adventurers congregate.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Friendships are made or renewed, and there
is also much trading.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>It was here,
during one of the sudden downpours that afflict the land, that Berant espied
three Barbarians with heavy bags of Gnollish loot and made bold to approach them.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-right:-2.55pt;text-indent:36.0pt'><span
style="mso-spacerun: yes"> </span>I do not understand all that transpired, but
business was conducted, for I saw coin change hands.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>Berant introduced their leader as “Wassail” and said that he
would allow me to join his party in their journey to Halas.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">   </span>With his companions impatient to start for
fair Qeynos, he had time for only a cursory farewell, leaving me alone with the
Barbarian party.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-right:-2.55pt;text-indent:36.0pt'>There was an
awkward pause, during which the three of them considered me with unswerving and
rather unfriendly eyes.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I do not doubt
that mockery would soon be made of me, much in the way of my travelling
companions from Qeynos.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Fortunately, or
perhaps unfortunately, a distraction was at hand.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>It so happened that a transaction was being finalised nearby.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>A young Human female, her brow emblazoned
with the mark of the Paladins of Rodcet Nife, was concluding a trade with an
Erudite adventurer.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>She handed over a
bag of gold and received in return a most exquisitely wrought chain tunic,
which she proceeded to shrug into.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>She
then bowed to the Erudite, and smiling with satisfaction, made towards the
entrance to the underground complexes of Blackburrow.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>Her passage took her by my new companions.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>Now, I have met many Paladins in
Qeynos, and have never failed to be impressed.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>They are a kind, generous and caring folk, strong in both their faith
and skill at arms, if perhaps a little strait-laced.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>Unfortunately for a Barbarian these admirable traits seem to
translate into “soft”, “boring”, and “gullible”.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>Wassail waited until she had just got by us before calling out:</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>“Do ye see yon Pally, striding out in the rain,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>With her brand new armor, made of brand new chain,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>With a lemon for a face, an’ a pea for a brain…</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>I’d not follow her in a party!”</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>I am rather disappointed,
especially in the light of subsequent events, that the first Barbarian “song” I
heard was this scandalous little ditty.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>Yet, even here there is evidence of unexpected creativity, for although
the tune is obviously a standard, the lyrics must have been made up on the
spot.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Caught off guard, the Paladin
started and spun around.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">   </span>The
Barbarians, of course, found this reaction most amusing.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>They laughed heartily, and not the polite
chuckles of the civilised, but the great bellows of the far north.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>The Paladin flushed and inquired
politely as to what they found so amusing.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>By her manner of speech she was a compatriot of mine.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I would venture North-Eastern Qeynos as her
place of origin.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Wassail, rather
boorishly, proceeded to mock her refined accent.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>He apparently had the strange belief that skill at arms and skill
at diction were somehow incompatible.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>The Paladin pointed this out, and suggested a more reasonable separation
– namely between those who could fight (and here she indicated herself) and
those who merely talked about how they could fight (and here she nodded towards
the three Barbarians).</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>The laughter stopped
instantly.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Wassail levered himself up
with astonishing speed for such a large individual and got straight up into her
face.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>His cohorts closed around.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I profess amazement at how swiftly such a
minor incident transformed itself into a potentially lethal one.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>Wassail growled at the Paladin
through his teeth.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>He spoke in his
native tongue, and although I do not understand what he said the general
meaning came over quite eloquently.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>It
was a sight, to see this Human girl, who would have been counted brawny in
other circumstances, diminished in comparison to the three hulking Barbarians
surrounding her.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I am not ashamed to
say I would have been much affeared in such a situation, but she seemed calm
and unafraid.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>It was only from my
vantage point that I could see her left leg twitching back and forth.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>Neither Barbarians nor Paladin
seemed prepared to back down, and I feared that bloodshed would ensue, but
fortunately there were others who were also witness to this distressing
incident.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>The Erudite merchant and
several Elves were on hand and took it upon themselves to interpose between the
warring parties.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Berant also reappeared
and applied some cold hard logic.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>His
argument fulfilled all the requirements of oratory.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>What?<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Would they fight
each other, and give the Gnolls a victory without them even having to strike a
blow?<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>It was swift, clear and stated in
a manner where refutation was quite impossible.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>Once again I find I must commend the good services of Berant to
your Graces.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>Eventually both sides retired
simultaneously, the Barbarians all the time shouting derision and various dire
threats upon the person of the Paladin, which she chose to ignore.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I confess I was most perturbed at the thought
of travelling in such uncouth company, but once we entered the tunnels leading
to Everfrost Wassail’s black mood dissipated as quickly as it had blown up, and
beyond a few cursory observations he ignored me.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>This I discovered to be a common feature of Barbarians.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Their moods are sudden and they are not
prone to dwell on the past.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>However, at
the time I thought it wise to not ask too many questions concerning our route
and destination, judging that Halas denizens of a more conducive nature could
be found in the city itself.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>We made a hard pace through the
cold, snowy peaks of Everfrost.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>The
canyons soar all around, even more spectacular than traveller’s tale would have
them.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">   </span>There is also a profusion of
wildlife to be found.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">   </span>Wolves, polar
bears and even a northern version of the large spider, camouflaged white and
covered in bristles as protection against the low temperatures.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Decaying skeletons are also common, rumoured
to be the result of a curse placed by an insane mage.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>Wassail explained that his people hunted them, for they often
carry weapons, which although rusty are effective yet.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Also the bones, if undamaged, sell well in
the great cities.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I found this last
distasteful, for I hold necromancy to be unholy.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>The Barbarians were not slow to sneer at my sensibilities.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>As I said, they are a pragmatic people, and
live but for the moment.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Nonetheless, I
could do nought but approve that my companions disposed of several of these semblances
of life as we proceeded.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>The canyons twisted and turned,
and the snow fell, such that even Wassail was unsure of our path on
occasions.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>He became most
frustrated.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>So, when he espied another
skeleton nearby he resolved to vent his rage upon it.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>With a great shout he charged the undead thing, hewing it with
his great two-handed sword.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>However,
this skeleton did not succumb as easily as the previous ones.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>It seemed to shrug the mighty blow off and
then, with an unholy light gleaming from its eye sockets, began to pummel the
unfortunate Wassail.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>This, I was to
learn later, was a “vengeful”, a breed of undead identical in appearance to the
decaying skeleton but possessing far more constitution and skill.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>The insane genius behind the undead scourge
includes them amongst his creations as a trap for overconfident Barbarians.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>Even so, such was the valor and
skill of my companions, I venture to suggest we could have emerged victorious,
but that by great misfortune a second and then a third of the foul things
charged into the fray, and our affairs soon became most desperate.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>When Wassail himself slumped to one knee,
his face pale and wan from loss of blood and his arm but weakly raised to fend
off the assaults of the foe, I feared that all of our ends had come.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>Then I heard a loud shout of “By
the power of Rodcet!” and a flurry of blue encircled Wassail, jerking him
upright in an instant.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Completely
revived, he lay on even more furiously.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>The Paladin we had scorned earlier ran past me at pace and began to
strike cunningly at our foes.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>With four
blades giving blows now the “vengefuls” soon lay in heaps at our feet.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>Wassail had been saved from
certain death, and he knew it.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>The
Northmen are proud, but not to the extent whereby they disdain to admit they
are wrong.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>He bowed before the Paladin
and thanked her in the name of himself and his companions, and bade her join
us.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Her name was Anthundorme of Qeynos,
and she accepted courteously, for Paladins do not belittle those whom they
aid.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Each Barbarian clasped her hand
and vowed friendship.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>All was smiles,
and I think only I saw her strive not to wince at their fearsome handclasps.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>Night beckoned, and it was
decided to camp.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Once a fire was lit,
Wassail began to pick amongst the bones of the undead, and Anthundorme
questioned him as to what he intended.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>She took my side in our earlier argument.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>It was her firm belief, she said, that the destruction of
necromancy to enable other necromancy is a policy of folly.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Wassail thought upon this, and finally gave
a great nod of his shaggy head.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>He
thereupon made a mighty vow that any bones he took from now on would be
delivered to the temple in Qeynos, and not sold for profit to greedy merchants,
from whence they went to who knew where.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>After we had supped, Wassail
asked the Paladin of Rodcet Nife, this Deity who she had called upon to heal him.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>This, of course, was an invitation no
Paladin could or would miss.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I prepared
myself with heavy heart for a pious exposition of temple theology, and indeed
Anthundorme did seem set on this expected path.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>Then she espied the golden flute I keep in my backpack.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>She smiled and asked if I could play the
tune “Soldier boys “.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>This was of
course a superfluous question.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>It is a
tune I learned some time ago, a simple rather erratic effort by a minor
composer.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>However, at her prompting I
took the flute and started to play the opening bars, at which Anthundorme sang
these words:</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><u><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>Rodcet’s Warriors.<o:p></o:p></span></u></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Accompaniment – Flute.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Pace: Brightly.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Oh, Rodcet is our Deity’s name,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>For Him we’re off and gone.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>We’re fighting for our faith and life,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Our swords are buckled on.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>We’re fighting, for,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Our only true love.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>His foes we do defy,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>He is the darling of our hearts,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>The God of life and joy.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>[chorus]</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Oh, Nife, Oh Nife, Oh Nife, Oh Nife Oh Nife!</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>We live for his employ,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>He is the darling of our hearts,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>The God of life and joy.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>We only take up sword and shield,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>For Him that dwells above,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>The greatest weapons we possess,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Are kindliness and love.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>The wounds, that bite,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Do not advance our cause.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>So much as all the care,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>In which we heal all those who ask,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>A favor with a prayer.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>[chorus]</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Our thoughts are with all of those,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Who’re fighting in the field.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>We know that we shall win at last,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>For goodness does not yield.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>We know that, soon,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>We can lay down our arms.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Norrath shall be at peace.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>For all her wars and hate and strife,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Shall someday come to cease.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>[chorus]</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Although I was glad to be able to add another song to my
collection, obviously from a technical point of view it leaves much to be
desired.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>The metre is disjointed and
the rhyme pattern crude, to put it mildly. <span style="mso-spacerun:
yes"> </span>Neither was the performance of a standard I hope we in the guild
would find acceptable.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Anthundorme’s
voice is<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>– distinctive – rather than
skilled.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Yet, as we sat around the
campfire that night, a days’ journey from Halas, I recall seeing the Paladin’s
eyes close as she sang.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I felt the
words burst from her very core, and, underlined by her actions earlier, I knew
at that moment that she sang what she really believed to be true.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I saw the nodding approval of that from the
Barbarians who had until recently been her enemies.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>In short, I witnessed in life what Master Lutestringer taught us
in year one basic theory – our art conveying feelings and ideas more readily,
in a few minutes, than could be done in a month of exposition.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>It was a humbling sight, and I beg you
tender my apologies to Master Lutestringer for my scepticism then of his
insights.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>Your Graces, I have just received
information from Marton Stringsinger that the mysterious Jallt has been seen in
Halas.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I go now to seek her out and
fulfil my mission.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I do not know what
to expect, except possibly, the unexpected.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>That this lady has had musical training would be too much to hope for,
but I remain confident that I will soon be able to present a complete archive
of this northern song phenomenon, and return safely to Qeynos.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Written this day by my hand,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Tagelied HalfElven, of the 6<sup>th</sup> Circle, Antonican
league of Bards.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>(You can find Tagelied, Wassail and Jallt on the Tholuxe
Paells server.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Anthundorme is resident
on the Bristlebane server, but is able to be in this story by some weird and
wonderful dimensional drift/time warp thingy).</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>PS Have you ever realised that “Rodcet Nife” is a near anagram
of “Fine Doctor”?</p>

</div>

